In .NET MAUI Shell, you can intercept back navigation and customize the back button using Shell attached properties and the `OnNavigating` event.

**1. Custom "Cancel" back button:**

```xml
<!-- EditProductPage.xaml -->
<ContentPage
    xmlns:shell="clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls"
    Shell.BackButtonBehavior="{StaticResource CancelBackButton}">

    <ContentPage.Resources>
        <BackButtonBehavior x:Key="CancelBackButton"
            TextOverride="Cancel"
            Command="{Binding GoBackCommand}" />
    </ContentPage.Resources>

    <!-- your form here -->
</ContentPage>
```

**2. Intercept navigation & show confirmation dialog:**

```csharp
// EditProductPage.xaml.cs
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override async void OnNavigatedFrom(NavigatedFromEventArgs args)
    {
        base.OnNavigatedFrom(args);
    }

    // This is the key method — override OnBackButtonPressed for HW/SW back
    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            ShowConfirmationDialog();
            return true; // cancel navigation
        }
        return base.OnBackButtonPressed(); // allow navigation
    }

    private async void ShowConfirmationDialog()
    {
        bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard and leave?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (leave)
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

**3. Wire up the "Cancel" button command in your ViewModel:**

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
private async Task GoBack()
{
    if (HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard and leave?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!leave) return;
    }
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**Key points:**

- `BackButtonBehavior.Command` replaces the default Shell back-button tap — it fires your command instead of navigating.
- `OnBackButtonPressed()` intercepts the Android/hardware back button. Return `true` to cancel.
- Both paths should funnel through the same confirmation logic, then call `Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..")` to actually navigate back.
